This is a demonstration of programming concepts that
form the basis of the Hilltop programming language.
This demonstration will show how a Flappy Bird-type
application is programmed.
Some syntactic elements will be omitted for simplicity.
FlappyBird
Hilltop borrows concepts from spreadsheets, where an
application is expressed by manipulating cells and their
values and other attributes (e.g., date format,
alignment).
In Hilltop, each cell represents a different type of
application component, including data, GUI widgets,
and even code. Cells are arranged hierarchically, and
different cell types have different attributes whose
values are defined using literal values or reactive
formulas that may depend on other cell attribute
values.
As in a spreadsheet, a Hilltop application runs when
cell attribute values change, causing other cell
attribute values to be recalculated.
FlappyBird

We start by defining some of the games more obvious
cells. Well define others as we go along.
FlappyBird is a cell that represents the application
itself. Each cell has a predefined type, such as
application, text, number, image, etc. An application-
type cell is also a window-type cell.
A cell may have one or more child cells that may be
defined in any order under its parent cell. Indentation
is used to indicate a parent-child relationship.
A . prefix is used to identify child cells.
FlappyBird

.GameOverText
.Score
.BestScore
Each cell has predefined attributes, and different cell
types have different predefined attributes. Attributes,
like cells, have predefined types, such as text, number,
date, Boolean, etc.
We continue by providing value definitions for various
cell attributes. A cells attributes are listed immediately
below the cells name and are indented.
A: prefix is used to identify cell attributes.
Orientation is an attribute of the FlappyBird
application cell that indicates the display orientation of
the application window. The value of Orientation is
defined as being equal to Portrait.
Highlighting is used to distinguish literal values from
cell and attribute names and other programming
syntax.
FlappyBird
:Orientation = Portrait

The Background cell has a URL attribute that may be
defined to indicate the location path and name of an
image file. Here, as no location path is specified, the
default location of the specified image file is the
location of the application itself.

X/Y coordinate values are provided to position the
background image within the application window. X=0
and Y=0 are located at the top left corner of the
application window. Units represent a percentage of
window width (for X) and height (for Y).
The Background cell also includes predefined height
and width attributes (omitted here) whose values may
be defined as needed to adapt the size of the
background image to the application window.
FlappyBird
:Orientation = Portrait
.Background
:URL = background.jpg
:X = 0
:Y = 0

The notation Cell<n> indicates that n instances of
cell are to be created automatically at runtime. Where
a single instance of a cell is desired, <1> need not be
specified, as a single instance of each cell is created
automatically at runtime by default. Cell<> represents
a metacell from which instances of cell will be created
programmatically at runtime (i.e., no instances will be
created automatically at runtime). Cell<name> may
be used to create a named cell instance.
A fixed number of column pairs may be specified that
enter from the right side of the display, move leftward,
and then reenter from the right side of the display
after they exit the left side of the display. Alternatively,
new column pairs may be created and destroyed
during game play as they enter and leave the display.
The latter approach is used here. Therefore,
Columns<> is used to indicate that instances of
Columns will be created programmatically at runtime.
FlappyBird<1>
:Orientation = Portrait
.Background<1>
:URL = background.jpg
:X = 0
:Y = 0
.Columns<>
.Bird<1>
.GameStartText<1>
.GameOverText<1>
.Score<1>
.BestScore<1>
Each column pair includes a top column and a bottom
column.
A Column child metacell is created with two instances
named Top and Bottom.
The top and bottom columns are both positioned
initially to the right of the display. Since their X
attributes have the same value, we may define their X
attribute once in the Column metacell.
Whenever an instance of Columns is created,
instances of its child cells are created as well.

:URL = topcolumn.jpg
<Bottom>
:URL = bottomcolumn.jpg
.Bird
.GameStartText
.GameOverText
.Score
The bottom of the top column is set to between 10%
and 30% from the top of the display.
The top of the bottom column is set to 30% of the
display height below the bottom of the top column.
Column<Top>:BottomY refers to the BottomY
attribute of the Column<Top> cell.
Like cells in a spreadsheet, attribute values that
depend on other attribute values are (unless otherwise
specified) automatically reevaluated (i.e., recalculated)
when the values on which they depend change.

.Bird
.GameStartText
The speed of each column is set to 4, which means that
they will move a distance equivalent to 4% of the
largest display dimension each second.
The heading of each column is set to 270 degrees
relative to the top of the display in its current
orientation.
The movement of the columns is controlled by a
physics engine that automatically changes their X and Y
attribute values as a function of the current values of
their speed and heading attributes.

The Destroyed attribute is defined to cause instances
of Columns to self-destruct once the top column
moves past the left side of the display.
The value of Destroyed is automatically reevaluated
whenever the RightX value of Column<Top>
changes.
FlappyBird
.Columns<>
:Destroyed = Yes If Column<Top>:RightX < 0

An AvoidedMe child cell is defined to keep track of
whether the bird has successfully passed a column pair.
As AvoidedMe is a Boolean data-type cell, we may
optionally define the value of its Value attribute on
the same line as the cells name.

A rule-type cell is evaluated whenever a change occurs
in the value of an attribute on which the rules
condition depends.
A rule-type child cell is defined here to add a point to
the score when the bird successfully passes a column
pair.

A GameState cell will be used to track the games
current state. Its initial value is set to Startup.
The birds gravity during game play is set to fall along
the Y axis at a rate of 3% per second
2
of the largest
display dimension, and 0 at other times. The birds
movement is controlled by the physics engine that
automatically changes their X and Y attribute values as
a function of the current values of its speed, heading,
and gravity attributes.
The bird is initialized (i.e., its attribute values are reset
to their initially defined values) if the value of
GameState changes to Playing.
FlappyBird
.Bird
:URL = flappy.jpg
:X = 20
:Y = 50
:Gravity =
3 If GameState = Playing
0 Otherwise
:Initialized = Yes If GameState = Playing

.GameOverText

.GameState = Startup
GameStartText appears only once, at game startup.
When the display is tapped, the GameStartText
instance is destroyed.
FlappyBird
.GameStartText = Tap the display to begin
:CenterX = 50
:CenterY = 50
:Destroyed = Yes if Display:tapped = Yes
.GameOverText
.Score
.BestScore
.GameState = Startup
GameOverText appears when the game is over. Its
visibility is evaluated whenever the value of
GameState changes.
GameOverText is a group-type cell under which
several child text cells are defined. Since the child cells
have the same CenterX attribute value, we may
define their CenterX attribute once at the
GameOverText cell.
FlappyBird
.GameOverText
:Visible = Yes If GameState = GameOver
:CenterX = 50
.GameOverLine = Game Over
:CenterY = 30
.ScoreLine = Score: + Score
:CenterY = 30
.BestScoreLine = BestScore: + BestScore
:CenterY = 50
.ReplayLine = Tap the screen to play again
:CenterY = 60
.Score
The initial values of Score and BestScore are set to 0.
Thereafter, Score is initialized (i.e., reset to the value
initially defined for it, namely 0) if the value of
GameState changes to Playing.
FlappyBird
.Score = 0
:Initialized = Yes If GameState = Playing
.BestScore = 0
.GameState = Startup
A rule-type cell is defined that is evaluated when the
display is tapped.
At application startup or after a game is over, tapping
the display will create the first instance of Columns
(after first destroying any current instances, where
Columns<*> refers to all Columns), and set the
current game state to Playing.
During a game, tapping the display will provide upward
acceleration to the bird.
FlappyBird
.Score = 0
:Initialized = Yes If GameState = Playing
.BestScore = 0
.GameState = Startup
.Rule: If Display is tapped
If GameState = (Startup or GameOver)
Columns<*>:Destroyed = Yes
Create Column
GameState = Playing
Else
Accelerate Bird by 3 for .5 seconds with
a heading 0
Another rule-type cell is defined to check when the
bird hits the ground or collides with a column.
FlappyBird
.Rule: If Display is tapped
If GameState = (Startup or GameOver)
Columns<*>:Destroyed = Yes
Create Column
GameState = Playing
Else
Accelerate Bird by 3 for .5 seconds with
a heading of 0
.Rule: If (Bird:BottomY >= 100) or
(Bird:Collided = Yes)
Columns<*>:Column<Top>:Speed = 0
Columns<*>:Column<Bottom>:Speed = 0
Bird:Speed = 0
If Score > BestScore
BestScore = Score
GameState = GameOver
The program is now complete.
